Introduction1.1 The investigationThis investigation will explore, through the use of simulations, the effectiveness of various preventative measures aimed at controlling the rate at which COVID-19 spreads through communities. For each trial the simulations will be altered to attempt to replicate preventative conditions introduced by the Australian government, and then discuss how this affects the exponential growth of the number of infected people. This will hopefully demonstrate why these measures are implemented and why they should be followed. 1.2 COVID-19 backgroundTowards the end of 2019 a new virus causing various symptoms including those of pneumonia and severe acute respiratory syndrome, emerged from the city of Wuhan, China. The World Health Organisation (WHO) were first made aware of this virus in late December 2019, and on the 12th of January 2020 they announced that the cause of these symptoms was a novel coronavirus, SARS-CoV-2, which became known as COVID-19. As the year continued COVID-19 spread around the globe and was declared a pandemic by the WHO on March 11th, 2020 [1]. 1.2 The curveOne of the factors that led to COVID-19 spreading so rapidly around the globe is how easily it infected those susceptible to the disease. For example, during May 2020, (the month during which COVID-19 was declared a pandemic), 82,591 new cases worldwide were being confirmed each day [1]. As the number of infected individuals skyrocketed, health care systems around the world were over-run. As such a common term has arisen called "flattening the curve". In this case, "the curve" is referring to a visual representation of the number of infected people over time. By governments implementing things such as social distancing, lockdowns, enforcing masks and rolling out vaccines they are attempting to slow the infection rate of COVID-19 to a rate at which healthcare systems can manage [2]. The model below visually illustrates the theoretical effects of social distancing on the number of people infected with COVID-19 over time:
Figure 1:Diagram from [3] website demonstrating why "flattening the curve" is important to ensure that the number of infected people does not exceed the healthcare systems capacity
If the government fails to flatten the curve then not everyone infected with COVID-19 will be able to be treated and many avoidable deaths will occur as a result [3]. In the simulations below the "curve" in discussion is referring to the graph of I(t) or the number of infected people over time. 1.3 Exponential growth and the scale factorWhen discussing the effectiveness of preventative measures it is beneficial to look at the scale factors for each simulation. For a virus which has a scale factor of 1.01 the number of infected people will increase by 1% each day [4]. A larger scale factor and percentage change means that the infected curve is much sharper and will likely be beyond that which health care systems can safely manage. Each of the simulations used in this investigation returns a graph as below:
In this graph the red line represents the "curve" or the number of infected people over time, the green and blue lines represent the number of susceptible and removed people, which are elaborated on later in this investigation. The next section of the investigation will focus only on the red line in the above graph, the infected curve. To calculate the exponential growth of infected people for my models an exponential regression is used (finds an exponential equation that best fits the infected curve). The "SciPy library" is used for this as below:
def exponential(x, a, b): return a*np.exp(-b*(x - day_list[max_value])**2) vars, cov = curve_fit(f=exponential, xdata=x_list, ydata=y_list, p0=[0, 0], bounds=(-np.inf, np.inf))
 This returns the required variables (A, B) for an exponential function in the form of y = Ae-B(t-c)2, where c is the day of the most infected cases, A is the number of infected cases at the turning point and t is time in days. This equation graphs to below:
The first point of inflection (point at which the curvature is inversed) for the above equation can be found by getting the second derivative and solving for d2y
dt2 = 0. After rounding to 0 decimal places, the day of the point of inflection is found. Another exponential regression can be used to find the exponential growth of realistic simulation data between day 0 and the previously evaluated, day of inflection as shown in the diagram below
Figure 2:Diagram showing where an exponential regression is used on real simulation data
 This gives an equation in the form y=AeBt, or a standard exponential growth equation which looks like this:
This equation represents the theoretical growth of the number of infected people over time and can be used to calculate a scale factor and percentage change for each model as below:y=AeBt Scale Factor=eB ∴ % change=(eB-1)×100These scale factors and exponential growth equations represent the unconstrained exponential growth of the number of infections over time. They do not account for the negative feedback (such as population size and recovery time) which would cause the curve to reach a turning point before displaying exponential decay and are instead a physically impossible extension of the initial exponential growth and are used to compare the infection rate under different limiting conditions [5]. 2. Compartmental Models2.1 Introduction to SIR modelsBoth simulations utilised are different takes on the compartmental Susceptible-Infectious-Removed (SIR) model. It divides a total population up into three groups: Susceptible: These people are considered healthy, they do not have the virus but are able to contract it. Infectious: These people are currently sick and, most importantly, are able to transmit the virus to the susceptible population. Removed: These people have either recovered (more on this in the assumptions section) or died, either way they are not considered susceptible and are unable to spread the virus. They are still considered part of the total population (N). These three groups can be represented mathematically as below:S(t) + I(t) + R(t) = NThe above represents the portions of the population that are susceptible (S(t)), infectious (I(t)) and removed (R(t)) as functions of time where N is the total population [6]. N also represents one of the first crucial assumptions of the SIR model. It assumes that N (the total population) is fixed, it does not increase or decrease. This means that people who die do not leave the population but are instead accounted for as removed. As the SIR model is generally used for short-term models, births and immigration are not accounted for however a reasonable degree of accuracy is still able to be maintained [6]. There are two other important variables to consider when investigating SIR models: 𝛽 is considered the force of the infection and is mathematically represented as 𝛽 = n×p where n is the average number of susceptible people any infectious person interacts with (an interaction is a situation between two people where the disease could be transmitted) on any given day, and p represents the probability of the virus transmitting from an infected person to a susceptible person [7]. 𝛾 is considered the recovery rate. 𝛾 is also the reciprocal of D (the amount of days it will take for an infected person to recover). 𝛾 can be represented mathematically as 𝛾=1
D [7]. 2.2 The basic SIR modelThe first model used for this investigation is the most basic version of the SIR model, which most other compartmental model are derived from. This model was developed by Ronald Ross, William Hamer et al in the early 20th century and is used to roughly predict what will happen if a virus with calculated properties enter a small community over a period of time [7]. In this investigation it will be used to predict what will happen and then compared to the second, realistic simulation. While this model not only assumes a fixed population (as above) it is also assumed that everyone who contracts the virus will recover in D number of days, with no account for age or the medical services where that person is located. With this in mind a system of differential equations is produced (these equations were first produced by Kermack and McKendrick in 1927) [8]:dS
dt = -𝛽SI
N dI
dt = 𝛽SI
N - 𝛾I dR
dt = 𝛾IAs these equations are for the rates of changes for S(t), I(t), R(t) they must be integrated before being graphed.The SciPy python library can be used to integrate these three equations over time by passing in a function which returns the derivative equations as well as a linspace from the NumPy library which starts at 0 and ends at the duration of the experiment. All this code can be seen as below:
#Define Beta and Gamma as described abovebeta, gamma = N*P, 1/D #Create NumPy linspace which starts at 0 and stops at duration of experimentduration = np.linspace(start=0, stop=DURATION, num=DURATION) #Function which returns the derivative equations described abovedef derivatives(y, t, POPULATION, beta, gamma): S, I, R = y dotS = -beta*S*(I/POPULATION) dotI = beta*S*(I/POPULATION) - gamma*I dotR = gamma*I return dotS, dotI, dotR #Integrate the above system of derivative equations using SciPy libraryresults = odeint(derivatives, intial_values, duration, args=(POPULATION, beta, gamma))S, I, R = results.T
 The python library MathPlotLib can then be used to graph these equations for S(t), I(t) and R(t) 2.3 Programmatic take on the SIR modelThe second simulation used is a programmatic take on a disease simulation programmed entirely in python. It simulates realistically daily activity and will be compared to the basic SIR simulation. Unlike the above classic SIR model, this simulation creates a population of people who all have a different number of interactions, a different probability of transmitting the disease and a different amount of time to fully recover from the disease. These are calculated using pythons Random library to get a random integer value for each of these between an upper and lower limit. By changing these upper and lower limits the simulation can be fine-tuned to fit certain situations. For example by decreasing the limits for the number of daily interactions a lock-down can be simulated, while still allowing for those that ignore restrictions. This is shown with the code below:
#Template for each person, holds valuesclass Person: def __init__(self, status, interactions, trans_prob, recov_time): self.status = status self.interactions = interactions self.trans_prob = trans_prob self.recov_time = recov_time #Assigns each person valuesdef create_person(): status = "susceptible" interactions = random.randint(min_interactions, max_interactions) trans_prob = round(random.uniform(min_trans_prob, max_trans_prob), 2)/10 recov_time = random.randint(min_recov_time, max_recov_time) return status, interactions, trans_prob, recov_time
 A function is then ran for every infectious person every day that either moves the infectious person into the removed category, or simulates interactions and uses the predetermined transmission probability to spread the virus to susceptible people. Due to the randomness of each simulation it was more accurate to run this simulation 10 times and then graph the average results, which are used to calculate the scale factor and percentage change. The entire simulation is a function that returns a list for the number of infected, susceptible and removed people on each day. These are then appended to a totals list and the NumPy library is used to get daily averages for each group as below:
def graph_list(input_list): output_array = [np.array(person) for person in input_list] return [np.mean(person) for person in zip(*output_array)] totals_lists = [graph_list(list) for list in totals_lists]
 When graphing the averages a much smoother and accurate curve is given in comparison to the graph of a single trial. This is then used for the exponential calculations. The line of best fit for my data is calculated with the below code:
def exponential(x, a, b): return a*np.exp(-b*(x - day_list[max_value])**2) vars, cov = curve_fit(f=exponential, xdata=x_list, ydata=y_list, p0=[0, 0], bounds=(-np.inf, np.inf)) def round_values(i): return round(i, 5) vars = list(map(round_values, vars.tolist())) equation = str(vars[0]) + 'e^-(' + str(vars[1]) + '(x - ' + str(max_value) + ')^2)'
 This returns an equation for the curve of the graph which is used in my calculations. 3. Real world data and how it applies to the simulations3.1 SimulationtownAll my simulations will be run within the pretend town Simulationtown. This town has the median Australian town population of 2,490 people and exhibits other median 2020 Australian characteristics [8]. The aim is to flatten the infected curve by reducing the exponential growth of "simulitis" (a factitious illness) and reduce the scale factor of simulitis within Simulationtown. 3.2 Creating an epidemicDue to COVID-19 changing frequently and the results of earlier research quickly becoming unreliable, a model of disease is used with similar properties to what is known of the original strain of COVID-19 (not delta or lambda variant). For simpliciy this model disease will be named "simulitis". In initial conditions (no preventative meausres in place) the average person in Simulationtown has between 5 and 10 interactions where a disease as contagious as COVID-19 could be transferred. A study by the US National Libary of Medicine released the below graph detailing the probability of COVID-19 transmission for the average person (there is another category of person called a super-spreader, who is far more effective at transmitting the disease, however they only make up 5% of the population, and so will be ignored for this investigation) [9]:
Figure 3:Graph detailing the probability of COVID-19 transmission for the average person
Assuming that the median unmasked interactions in Simulationtown occur at a distance of ≈0.5 metres, simulitis is assigned a probability of transmission of 50% when no masks are worn [9]. Studies by the Lancet Regional Health Journal found the median COVID-19 recovery time in Australia to be 16, with an interquartile range of 11 to 24 days [10]. Simulitis will exhibit the same properties. 3.3 Simulitis with no preventative measuresThe first simulations will investigate what happens if one person infected with simulitis enters Simulationtown with no preventative measures in place. The basic SIR simulation is run with the following parameters:
#Population SizePOPULATION = 2490 #Prob of transmissionPROB = 0.5 #Num of interactions (between 5 and 10)NUM = 7.5 #Recovery time (days)RECOVERY = 16

Applying individual preventative measures4.1 Social DistancingOne of the first and most basic preventative measures implemented was enforced social distancing. The Australian government heavily encouraged people to keep a distance of 1.5 meters from one another [11]. However this was rarely enforced and due to most peoples' inability to judge and maintain 1.5m distance, it most likely resulted in each person keeping about 1 meter of distance from every other person on average. At a distance of a meter, the probability of transmission decreases from 0.5 to 0.06 [9]. Keeping the number of interactions the same, the basic SIR simulation can be ran with the following parameters:

 7. Conclusion7.1 Effectiveness within SimulationtownAs shown in the above table of results the least effective way of stopping simulitis was obviously doing nothing. With a scale factor of 3.76 in this scenario simulitis spread scarily fast and infected everyone in the Simulationtown in a matter of days. At the time of writing this (July 2021), Australia has had a total of 34'130 with 924 deaths [13]. This means the death rate for simulitis (and COVID-19) can be calculated as below:924
34130×100=2.7%With no preventative measures in Simulationtown, 67 deaths occur as a result. These deaths are very preventable as shown with the other simulations. Implementing just basic lock-downs reduced the scale factor to 1.74, less than half of what it was before. A smaller scale factor directly correlates to a flatter curve, and therefore less preventable deaths. Using only enforced mask-wearing was slightly more effective than lockdowns with a scale factor of 1.68. By far the most effective single preventative measure was social distancing with a scale factor of only 1.39. The least effective combined preventative measures was the combination of lockdowns and masks with a scale factor of 1.12. While this was significantly lower than any of the individual preventative measures, it was much higher than any of the other combined preventative measures who all had scale factors of 0. Obviously implementing social distancing, masks and lockdowns is the most effective under any circumstance, something which was adopted by most governments around the world. 7.2 LimitationsWhen creating this investigation there were a number of generalisations made about the population in order to create semi-realistic results. In reality effective social distancing is very hard to maintain and enforce. This could be due to people ignoring guidelines, misunderstanding how big 1.5 meters is or social distancing just being impractical to the point where it is completely ignored such as in certain areas of schools and in shopping centres. Masks are also problematic due to people not wearing them properly, rendering them almost useless. The anti-mask movement is also a big factor that was not considered in this investigation. Large groups of people not adhering to social distancing and mask guidelines gather in large groups, greatly increasing the probability of transmission among them [14]. Lockdowns in this simulation, though fairly realistic do not consider forced quarantines. While the average, non-infectious person may maintain 1-2 daily interactions, those diagnosed are, in most circumstances, forced to self-isolate, reducing their interactions to 0 [15]. However there are still many who are either undiagnosed or ignore the lockdowns, so they are accounted for in the simulations. Another factor not accounted for in the simulations is vaccine roll-out. This is due to very little being known about them and how they affect transmission probability. Many people are also unvaccinated, due to the slow roll-out in Australia, or because they refuse to get the vaccination, making it hard to simulate such conditions. The initial number of infected individuals was also not changed from 1 throughout the investigation. Fortunately all the simulations with a single person give an equation for exponential growth in the form of y=Aekt. It is simple to get the equation for growth with n number of initial infected individuals as below:y=Aekt (1 initial infected) y=n×Aekt These can be graphed as below:
n=1n=57.3 ClosingIn conclusion, any sort of preventative measure will be better than none. While this investigation explored the success of various preventative measures, there are a few factors that will have a greater influence on the success rather than the measure itself. Certain aspects such as the speed at which the measures are implemented, how they are enforced and how the public adopts them have a much greater impact on the spread of disease. Taking New Zealand for example, they quickly implemented extreme lockdowns and heavily encouraged masks and social distancing [17], even locking down the city of Auckland in response to a handful of cases [18]. When compared to the UK, a county infamous for its poor handling of the COVID-19 situation, the effect of correct implementation of preventative measures becomes clear. The graph below shows the number of cases per million people from March 1st to July 1st 2020 [19]:
While these countries both implemented similar measures, the way they were implemented as well as the public's receptiveness to them had a great impact on their success. Hopefully this investigation helps to demonstrate to the public the importance of preventative measures and the effects that they have on the growth of diseases within their communities.
